def min_arrays(nums):
    def gcd(a, b):
        return a if b == 0 else gcd(b, a % b)

    total_gcd = nums[0]
    for num in nums[1:]:
        total_gcd = gcd(total_gcd, num)

    return 2 if total_gcd == 1 else 1
```

    The algorithm first finds the total GCD (greatest common divisor) of all the elements in the array. If the total GCD is 1, that means the array can't be split into a single subarray and satisfy the condition of having a GCD greater than 1. In this case, the minimum number of subarrays required is 2. Otherwise, if the total GCD is greater than 1, the entire array can be considered as a single subarray meeting the condition, so the answer is 1. The gcd function is a helper function that computes the GCD of two integers using the Euclidean algorithm.

